{"id":"1407.2952","submitter":"Mohamed Amin Ben Sassi Dr","authors":"Mohamed Amin Ben Sassi and Sriram Sankaranarayanan and Xin Chen and\n  Erika Abraham","title":"Linear Relaxations of Polynomial Positivity for Polynomial Lyapunov\n  Function Synthesis","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.DS","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this paper, we examine linear programming (LP) based relaxations for\nsynthesizing polynomial Lyapunov functions to prove the stability of polynomial\nODEs. A common approach to Lyapunov function synthesis starts from a desired\nparametric polynomial form of the polynomial Lyapunov function. Subsequently,\nwe encode the positive-definiteness of the function, and the\nnegative-definiteness of its derivative over the domain of interest. Therefore,\nthe key primitives for this encoding include: (a) proving that a given\npolynomial is positive definite over a domain of interest, and (b) encoding the\npositive definiteness of a given parametric polynomial, as a constraint on the\nunknown parameters. We first examine two classes of relaxations for proving\npolynomial positivity: relaxations by sum-of-squares (SOS) programs, against\nrelaxations that produce linear programs. We compare both types of relaxations\nby examining the class of polynomials that can be shown to be positive in each\ncase. Next, we present a progression of increasingly more powerful LP\nrelaxations based on expressing the given polynomial in its Bernstein form, as\na linear combination of Bernstein polynomials. The well-known bounds on\nBernstein polynomials over the unit box help us formulate increasingly precise\nLP relaxations that help us establish the positive definiteness of a polynomial\nover a bounded domain. Subsequently, we show how these LP relaxations can be\nused to search for Lyapunov functions for polynomial ODEs by formulating LP\ninstances. We compare our approaches to